<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
Female: A large (11-13 mm) black and yellow 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nomada" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Nomada</taxonomicName>
species. Yellow maculations are present in the pronotal lobes, tegula, as two small spots on the scutellum and as large yellow spots on the sides of tergites 1-3, that become bands in tergites 4-5 (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F6661792" captionText="Figure 3. Nomada sexfasciata (Panzer, 1799) (Remich, specimen MNHNL 25076). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view; c. Face, frontal view showing maculations, mandibles, clypeus, labrum and longitudinal carina; d. Face, lateral view showing elongated malar area. Scale bars = 1 mm. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501349" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">3</figureCitation>
a and b). The head presents a sharp longitudinal carina between the antennae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F6661792" captionText="Figure 3. Nomada sexfasciata (Panzer, 1799) (Remich, specimen MNHNL 25076). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view; c. Face, frontal view showing maculations, mandibles, clypeus, labrum and longitudinal carina; d. Face, lateral view showing elongated malar area. Scale bars = 1 mm. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501349" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">3</figureCitation>
c). Yellow maculations are present on the mandibles (apex simple), the clypeus and labrum, the malar area, the para-ocular area and on the ventral surface of the scape (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F6661792" captionText="Figure 3. Nomada sexfasciata (Panzer, 1799) (Remich, specimen MNHNL 25076). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view; c. Face, frontal view showing maculations, mandibles, clypeus, labrum and longitudinal carina; d. Face, lateral view showing elongated malar area. Scale bars = 1 mm. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501349" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">3</figureCitation>
c). The malar area is characteristically long with a protruding lower face (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F6661792" captionText="Figure 3. Nomada sexfasciata (Panzer, 1799) (Remich, specimen MNHNL 25076). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view; c. Face, frontal view showing maculations, mandibles, clypeus, labrum and longitudinal carina; d. Face, lateral view showing elongated malar area. Scale bars = 1 mm. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501349" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">3</figureCitation>
d) and the labrum is rounded, without a tooth (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F6661792" captionText="Figure 3. Nomada sexfasciata (Panzer, 1799) (Remich, specimen MNHNL 25076). a. Dorsal view; b. Lateral view; c. Face, frontal view showing maculations, mandibles, clypeus, labrum and longitudinal carina; d. Face, lateral view showing elongated malar area. Scale bars = 1 mm. Photos: MNHNL. Background edited using GIMP 2.8.22 (The GIMP Development Team 2020)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.9.e64027.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/501349" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">3</figureCitation>
e).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Voucher specimen (MNHNL25076): Adult female. Body length of 12 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Ecology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
An univoltine species that parasites 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Scopoli" authorityYear="1770" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Eucera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eucera" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Eucera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
nests, with a flight season spanning from late April until late July on the European continent (
<bibRefCitation author="Amiet, F." journalOrPublisher="Fauna Helvetica 20. Apidae 5: Ammobates, Ammobatoides, Anthophora, Biastes, Ceratina, Dasypoda, Epeoloides, Epeolus, Eucera, Macropis, Melecta, Melitta, Nomada, Pasites, Tetralonia, Thyreus, Xylocopa." pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643129" refString="Amiet, F., Herrmann, M., Mueller, A, Neumeyer, R., 2007. . Fauna Helvetica 20. Apidae 5: Ammobates, Ammobatoides, Anthophora, Biastes, Ceratina, Dasypoda, Epeoloides, Epeolus, Eucera, Macropis, Melecta, Melitta, Nomada, Pasites, Tetralonia, Thyreus, Xylocopa. 5" volume="5" year="2007">Amiet et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" type="conservation">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Conservation</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Panzer" baseAuthorityYear="1799" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Nomada" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Nomada sexfasciata" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexfasciata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027">Nomada sexfasciata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is classified under the IUCN category &quot;Least Concern (LC)&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="Nieto, A." journalOrPublisher="Luxembourg: Publications Office of the European Union" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643307" refString="Nieto, A., Roberts, S. P.M., Kemp, J., Rasmont, P., Kuhlmann, M., Garcia Criado, M., Biesmeijer, J. C., Bogusch, P., Dathe, H. H., De la Rua, P., De Meulemeester, T., Dehon, M., Dewulf, A., Ortiz-Sanchez, F. J., Lhomme, P., Pauly, A., Potts, S. G., Praz, C., Quaranta, M., Radchenko, V. G., Scheuchl, E., Smit, J., Straka, J., Terzo, M., Tomozii, B., Window, J., Michez, D., 2014. European Red List of bees. Luxembourg: Publications Office of the European Union" title="European Red List of bees" year="2014">Nieto et al. 2014</bibRefCitation>
), but it is included in the National Red Lists and Red Data Books of Great Britain, the Netherlands and Sweden (
<bibRefCitation author="Slieker, Frans J A" journalOrPublisher="Trends in Ecology &amp; Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="64027" refId="B6643447" refString="Smit J. Nomada sexfasciata. The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/19198614/21462569 2020-08-11T00:00:00+03:00" year="2021">Smit 2014</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
